data.content:
Here are the refactored tests using each framework's native exception assertions:

**MSTest:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsException()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<InvalidOperationException>(
        () => processor.ProcessOrder(new Order()));

    Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
}
```

**xUnit:**
```csharp
[Fact]
public void ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsException()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor();

    var ex = Assert.Throws<InvalidOperationException>(
        () => processor.ProcessOrder(new Order()));

    Assert.Equal("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
}
```

**NUnit:**
```csharp
[Test]
public void ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsException()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor();

    var ex = Assert.Throws<InvalidOperationException>(
        () => processor.ProcessOrder(new Order()));

    Assert.That(ex.Message, Is.EqualTo("Order must contain at least one item"));
}
```

Each version asserts the exact exception type is thrown **and** returns the exception instance so you can verify the message. If no exception (or a wrong type) is thrown, the test fails automatically—no `try/catch` or `Assert.Fail` needed.

> Note: MSTest v3 uses `Assert.ThrowsException<T>`; the example above uses `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` from MSTest v4. Use whichever matches your version.
